result.execSummary:
The defendant Austin Robert Kraemer was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Neglecting A Child-Specified Harm Did Not Occur And Child Under 6 Years Of Age, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.21(2).
  • Possession of Narcotic Drugs, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(am).
  • Operating A Motor Vehicle While Under The Influence-2ND Offense With A Minor Child In the Vehicle, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Court finds defendant is not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration program but is eligible for the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program after serving 1 year of Initial confinement.

Court advised due to felony conviction the defendant is prohibited from firearm possession and defendant's voting rights are suspended and may not vote until civil rights are restored.

records.addlTxt: counts one and two.
Count three.
Count two.

Defendant Austin Robert Kraemer appeared by video, in custody.  Attorney Thomas Evangelos Harris appeared by video for Austin Robert Kraemer.  Attorney Mallory R Davis in court for State of Wisconsin. 
Plea and sentencing hearing held. Court held colloquy with the defendant regarding his right to have an in-person hearing. Parties have reached an agreement. State places offer on the record. Defense and defendant are in agreement.

AS TO COUNTS 1, 2 AND 3: Defendant changes plea(s) to GUILTY. Defendant examined as to plea, advised of Constitutional Rights and the maximum penalties. Defendant further advised that if not a US citizen, deportation is possible. Court found that the defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived rights.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights form, Addendum, and Elements/Jury Instructions received and filed. Parties stipulate to the Criminal Complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea(s).  Court found defendant GUILTY and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record. 

Sentencing proceeded. Statements by parties and defendant. 

AS TO COUNT 1: The court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM term in the Wisconsin State Prison of 3 YEARS AND 6 MONTHS, concurrent to any other sentence, with credit for 203 DAYS time served, the term of INITIAL CONFINEMENT is 1 YEAR AND 6 MONTHS, the term of EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 2 YEARS. 

AS TO COUNT 2: The court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM term in the Wisconsin State Prison of 3 YEARS AND 6 MONTHS, concurrent to any other sentence, with credit for 203 DAYS time served, the term of INITIAL CONFINEMENT is 1 YEAR AND 6 MONTHS, the term of EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 2 YEARS. 

AS TO COUNT 3: The court sentenced the defendant to serve 9 MONTHS in the House of Correction, with credit for 203 days time served, concurrent to any other sentence.
Court ordered Defendant to pay a fine of $700.00 plus all costs, fees, and surcharges (including DNA and IID). Court ordered AODA Assessment and Driver Safety Plan. Defendant to cooperate with any recommended treatment. Court ordered Defendant's driving privileges revoked for a period of 2 YEARS, consecutive.  Court ordered Defendant restricted to operation of vehicles equipped with an Ignition Interlock Device (IID) for 2 YEARS.

CONDITIONS OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION
-Parenting classes.
-Mental health evaluation, take all prescribed medications.
-AODA assessment, comply with recommended treatment.
-Absolute sobriety.
-SCRAM and random UA's.
-Driver's license suspended for 6 months, consecutive, as to count 2.
-Court ordered that all court costs, fines, surcharges (DNA) be paid through collection by the Department of Corrections in an amount or percentage the Department (DOC) determines to be reasonable and as a condition of extended supervision.  DOC shall collect those sums.  Any amount remaining due and owing is subject to civil judgment and/or tax intercept or other means. Any cash bail on deposit to apply and the remaining balance to be returned to the poster.
-Court WAIVES all non-mandatory court costs, fees, and surcharges due to inability to pay.
-Provide DNA Sample.
-Restitution is set at ZERO.

*Court finds defendant is NOT eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program but IS ELIGIBLE for the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program after serving 1 year of initial confinement.
*Court advised defendant of right to seek post conviction relief.
*Court advised due to felony conviction the defendant is prohibited from firearm possession, and defendant's voting rights are suspended and may not vote until civil rights are restored.
